e access with authorization2star  aJewish Entanglements in the Atlantic World represents the first collective attempt to reframe the study of colonial and early American Jewry within the context of Atlantic History. From roughly 1500 to 1830, the Atlantic World was a tightly intertwined swathe of global powers that included Europe, Africa, North and South America, and the Caribbean. How, when, and where do Jews figure in this important chapter of history? This book explores these questions and many others. The essays of this volume foreground the connectivity between Jews and other population groups in the realms of empire, trade, and slavery, taking readers from the shores of Caribbean islands to various outposts of the Dutch, English, Spanish, and Portuguese empires.Jewish Entanglements in the Atlantic World revolutionizes the study of Jews in early American history, forging connections and breaking down artificial academic divisions so as to start writing the history of an Atlantic world influenced strongly by the culture, economy, politics, religion, society, and sexual relations of Jewish people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAFRICAN HIST & DIASPORA. 4aJEWISH STUDIES. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Imperialism.2bisacsh  aAtlantic History paradigm, Jews, American Jewish history, Atlantic revolutions, slavery, Sephardic Jews.1 aBen-Ur, Aviva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Ur, Aviva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDixon, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlooster, Wim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlooster, Wim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMirvis, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewm